In this case I think there are 3 points to keep in mind: 1. Start slowly: Depending on your current level, build up walking endurance first, then sprinting/jump-rope/shadow boxing etc. Once integrated and you have energy to spare, introduce low tempo running. The key is to integrate it slowly and let your body have rest when it needs to. Reducing stress in other areas of life will mean you have more resources left for endurance training. 2. Donâ€™t train cardio until failure: I.e. Donâ€™t do extreme cardio to the point your mouth is hanging open and youâ€™re gasping for air. If you canâ€™t breathe through your nose anymore, youâ€™ve probably gone too far. Reserve the times where you have to surpass your limits for highly special occasions. Plan them in such a way you have multiple days off to relax and recover if you decide to do so. 3. Enjoyment: Choose a form of cardio you genuinely enjoy (I prefer sprints and shadow boxing). Your attitude should be one that is opening and exploring new possibilities, this activates restorative processes throughout the body. What this means is that in 100g of peanut butter you'd have 10g of saturated fat, 25g of MUFA and 12.5g of PUFA. For someone who is relatively healthy these PUFA levels could be manageable but probably still not very healthy. Interestingly enough, there have been conscious efforts in the last 40 years to make peanuts more monounsaturated.
